Model & RoPE & Parameters & Loss & Samples/sec \\
\midrule
Baseline & No & 16.7M & 3.366 & 103 \\
STLM-Universal & No & 9.38M & 3.384 & 103 \\
\textbf{Baseline} & \textbf{Yes} & 16.6M & 3.405 & 98 \\
\textbf{STLM-Universal} & \textbf{Yes} & \textbf{9.24M} & \textbf{3.398} & \textbf{100} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Results at small scale (Depth=8). Peak VRAM is dominated by activations rather than parameters and therefore remains constant (\~11.5 GB in this config).}
\end{table}

At this intermediate scale, full weight sharing acts as a strong regularizer, allowing the Universal model to remain extremely competitive while slashing parameter count by 45\%.

\subsection{Scaling and the RoPE Synergy (Depth=16, Embed=512)}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcccc}
\toprule
Model & RoPE & Parameters & Loss & Reduction \\
\midrule
Baseline & No & 58.7M & 3.413 & 0\% \\
STLM-Universal & No & 19.3M & 3.421 & -67\% \\
\textbf{Baseline} & \textbf{Yes} & 58.4M & 3.421 & 0\% \\
\textbf{STLM-Universal} & \textbf{Yes} & \textbf{19.0M} & \textbf{3.409} & \textbf{-67\%} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Results at larger depth. Parameter count remains constant for the Universal model as depth increases.}
\end{table}

At Depth 16, the synergy between RoPE and weight sharing becomes manifest. The \textbf{STLM-Universal + RoPE} (3.409) actually \textbf{outperforms the Baseline + RoPE} (3.421) despite being \textbf{3x smaller} in parameter count. This confirms that modern positional encodings are the missing link for stable and performant recurrent Transformers.

\subsection{Memory and Throughput Considerations}

While weight sharing significantly reduces model storage and checkpoint size, peak VRAM usage and inference latency remain similar across variants. This is expected, as activation memory and FLOPs scale with depth, not parameter count. The primary advantages of shared-weight models are reduced storage, improved cache locality, and suitability for deployment on memory-constrained devices.

\subsection{Limitations}

While our results are promising, several limitations should be noted:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The use of machine-translated data for the French TinyStories dataset may introduce translation artifacts;
    \item The findings are currently limited to the simplified narrative domain of TinyStories and may not immediately generalize to complex factual reasoning;
    \item Although weight sharing reduces storage and memory footprint, it does not reduce the total FLOPs required for inference, as the number of computational passes remains tied to the model depth.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Discussion}

The success of Universal Transformers in this setting contrasts with earlier reports of convergence difficulties. We hypothesize that two factors contribute to this stability: (1) RoPE decouples positional information from layer index, avoiding conflicts under weight reuse; and (2) the simplified structure of TinyStories reduces long-range compositional complexity, making recurrent depth refinement effective.

\section{Conclusion}

This work provides empirical evidence that Transformer parameter redundancy is substantial, particularly in low-resource regimes. On French TinyStories, we show that:

\begin{itemize}
    \item At very small scale (8M--13M parameters), full weight sharing outperforms standard Transformers.
    \item At small-to-medium scale (18M--45M parameters), partial sharing offers the best accuracy, while full sharing achieves up to 60\% compression with negligible loss.
\end{itemize}

These findings support the use of shared-weight Transformers for Green AI and edge deployment. Future work will explore \textbf{knowledge distillation}, using Shared-FFN models as teachers for Universal students, to further close the remaining performance gap at scale.

